Dear Adriene,

I started this yoga challenge a few days before the new year. Though I've never been a sucker for resolutions, I told myself that this year I wanted to be more active and to be more in tune with my body and spirit. I'm committing to 20-30 minutes of SOME kind physical activity daily. I figured why not try something I could grow to actually enjoy, that way it won't feel like exercise. I've always admired the practice of yoga, but I never made any real effort towards it. I'd always end up laughing at myself either because of how out of shape I was or simply because I wouldn't take it seriously. But somehow, I've just completed day 12 of this journey and something in me just knows I will make it to day 30 (and when I do, I'll do it again!). It really is insane when you start to notice the progress you and your body are making. I don't know if I would be so far along in this journey if I had clicked on any other yoga instructor's page! Adriene, you make it okay to laugh at yourself and to not take things too seriously. I mean, name another yoga instructor who shamelessly delivers such cheesy jokes! Thank you for bringing such light and energy and fun to your yoga videos. Thank you for giving us options as learners. Thank you for your daily words of encouragement. You are appreciated. See you in the comments section on day 30 :)

Just wanted to say hello and thanks for putting yourself and your yoga out there for us. I started doing yoga many years ago, but actually put the physical part of the process into the over-thinking at the beginning of March. I had the video of the 20 minute beginner session saved on my computer for "when I got around to it."

Getting around to it for me meant finally coming to the realization for the need of a self-efficacious daily process for my health; revealed by an empathetic process wrapped up in the drama of an office narcissist. Beginning my yoga practice actually set forward the processes that I spent four years studying in college and will continue to study in whatever form makes the most sense going forward (graduate school, culinary school, dog walking school, Zen and the Art of Honda Maintenance, whatever...). I have a psychology degree. And I work in a psych lab. It's a strange working environment, to say the least; but when the medical doctor, from India, who handled the lab with grace and ease, recommends you undertake a yoga practice to deal with the currently (at the time) frazzling empathetic sensitivity ‚Äì a gift that led you to the profession in the first place ‚Äì you listen....

Anyway, I wanted to say thank you for being a part of the transformation into the human that I am becoming. I now embody first hand experimental evidence in a fresh yoga practice in one's early 30s. I would now feel more inclined to recommend a yoga practice to a (potential) client if I end up undertaking the whole counselor track that I'm thinking about.

So, I've learned this: Just keep showing up. That's all you gotta do. And don't forget to laugh.

So, thanks. And I thank everyone else too. And I thank myself. Okay, bye.
